We will consider a quantum walk $W:\ell^2({\mathbb{Z}}) \otimes {\mathbb{C}}^2 \to \ell^2({\mathbb{Z}}) \otimes {\mathbb{C}}^2 =: {\mathscr{H}}_1$, defined by a quasiperiodic sequence of coins. In the present section, we will define precisely the model, which arises via a one-dimensional representation of a two-dimensional quantum walk in a magnetic field. However, we emphasize that the one-dimensional model can be defined and studied without reference to the two-dimensional model. We explain the connection to two-dimensional magnetic quantum walks in detail in Section <a href="#sec:origins" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="sec:origins">3</a>.

Let us write the standard basis of ${\mathscr{H}}_1$ as $$\delta_n^s = \delta_n \otimes e_s, \quad n \in {\mathbb{Z}}, \, s \in \{+,-\},$$ where $\{\delta_n:n \in {\mathbb{Z}}\}$ denotes the standard basis of $\ell^2({\mathbb{Z}})$ and $e_+ = [1,0]^\top$, $e_-=[0,1]^\top$ denotes the standard basis of ${\mathbb{C}}^2$. For an element $\psi \in {\mathscr{H}}_1$, we write its coordinates as $\psi_n^s = \langle \delta_n^s, \psi \rangle$ so that $$\psi = \sum_{n\in{\mathbb{Z}}}\left( \psi_n^+ \delta_n^+ + \psi_n^- \delta_n^- \right),$$ where $\psi^+,\psi^- \in \ell^2({\mathbb{Z}})$. Viewing ${\mathscr{H}}_1 \cong \ell^2({\mathbb{Z}},{\mathbb{C}}^2)$, it is natural to also put $\psi_n = [\psi_n^+, \psi_n^-]^\top$. Recall that a quantum walk $W$ is specified by the iteration of a suitable unitary operator. Choosing a sequence of unitary coins $$Q_n = \begin{bmatrix} q_{n}^{11} & q_n^{12} \\ q_{n}^{21} & q_n^{22} \end{bmatrix} \in {\mathbb{U}}(2,{\mathbb{C}}),$$ and a parameter $\lambda \in [0,1]$, the walks we consider are given by $$\label{eq:moddefs:walkDef}
 W = S_{\lambda}    Q,$$ where $Q$ acts coordinatewise via $Q_n$ (i.e., $[Q\psi]_n =Q_n\psi_n$) and $S_\lambda$ is given by $$\label{eq:moddefs:slambdaDef}
S_\lambda\delta_n^\pm = \lambda \delta_{n\pm 1}^\pm \pm \lambda' \delta_n^\mp, \quad  \lambda' = \sqrt{1-\lambda^2}.$$ The reader may readily verify that $S_\lambda$, $Q$, and $W$ are all unitary. We call a walk of the form <a href="#eq:moddefs:walkDef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:moddefs:walkDef">[eq:moddefs:walkDef]</a> a *split-step walk* with *coupling constant* $\lambda$.

Let us write the standard basis of ${\mathscr{H}}_1$ as $$\delta_n^s = \delta_n \otimes e_s, \quad n \in {\mathbb{Z}}, \, s \in \{+,-\},$$ where $\{\delta_n:n \in {\mathbb{Z}}\}$ denotes the standard basis of $\ell^2({\mathbb{Z}})$ and $e_+ = [1,0]^\top$, $e_-=[0,1]^\top$ denotes the standard basis of ${\mathbb{C}}^2$. For an element $\psi \in {\mathscr{H}}_1$, we write its coordinates as $\psi_n^s = \langle \delta_n^s, \psi \rangle$ so that $$\psi = \sum_{n\in{\mathbb{Z}}}\left( \psi_n^+ \delta_n^+ + \psi_n^- \delta_n^- \right),$$ where $\psi^+,\psi^- \in \ell^2({\mathbb{Z}})$. Viewing ${\mathscr{H}}_1 \cong \ell^2({\mathbb{Z}},{\mathbb{C}}^2)$, it is natural to also put $\psi_n = [\psi_n^+, \psi_n^-]^\top$. Recall that a quantum walk $W$ is specified by the iteration of a suitable unitary operator. Choosing a sequence of unitary coins $$Q_n = \begin{bmatrix} q_{n}^{11} & q_n^{12} \\ q_{n}^{21} & q_n^{22} \end{bmatrix} \in {\mathbb{U}}(2,{\mathbb{C}}),$$ and a parameter $\lambda \in [0,1]$, the walks we consider are given by $$\label{eq:moddefs:walkDef}
 W = S_{\lambda}    Q,$$ where $Q$ acts coordinatewise via $Q_n$ (i.e., $[Q\psi]_n =Q_n\psi_n$) and $S_\lambda$ is given by $$\label{eq:moddefs:slambdaDef}
S_\lambda\delta_n^\pm = \lambda \delta_{n\pm 1}^\pm \pm \lambda' \delta_n^\mp, \quad  \lambda' = \sqrt{1-\lambda^2}.$$ The reader may readily verify that $S_\lambda$, $Q$, and $W$ are all unitary. We call a walk of the form <a href="#eq:moddefs:walkDef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:moddefs:walkDef">[eq:moddefs:walkDef]</a> a *split-step walk* with *coupling constant* $\lambda$.

We are now ready to define our main model. Given coupling constants $\lambda_1,\lambda_2 \in [0,1]$, a frequency $\Phi \in {\mathbb{T}}:= {\mathbb{R}}/{\mathbb{Z}}$, and a phase $\theta \in {\mathbb{T}}$, we consider the walk $$W_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,\Phi,\theta} = S_{\lambda_1}Q_{\lambda_2,\Phi,\theta}$$ where the coins $Q_n = Q_{\lambda_2,\Phi,\theta,n}$ are given by $$\begin{aligned}
 \label{eq:moddefs:coinDef}
 Q_n = Q_{\lambda_2,\Phi,\theta,n} = 
 \begin{bmatrix}
\lambda_2 \cos(2\pi(n\Phi+\theta)) + i\lambda_2'
& -\lambda_2 \sin(2\pi(n\Phi+\theta))\\ 
 \lambda_2\sin(2\pi(n\Phi+\theta)) 
 & \lambda_2 \cos(2\pi(n\Phi+\theta)) - i\lambda_2'
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{aligned}$$ By an argument using minimality of $\theta \mapsto \theta+\Phi$ and strong operator convergence, there is for each $\lambda_1,\lambda_2$ and irrational $\Phi$ a fixed set $\Sigma_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,\Phi}\subseteq \partial {\mathbb{D}}$ with $$\sigma(W_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,\Phi,\theta}) = \Sigma_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2, \Phi} \text{ for every } \theta \in {\mathbb{T}}.$$ Working out the relevant product, the reader can check that the action of $W = W_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,\Phi,\theta}$ in coordinates is given as $$\begin{aligned}
_n^+ & = \lambda_1 \left((\lambda_2 \cos(2\pi((n-1)\Phi+\theta)) + i\lambda_2')\psi_{n-1}^+ -\lambda_2 \sin(2\pi((n-1)\Phi+\theta))\psi_{n-1}^-\right)  \\
        & \qquad        -\lambda_1' \left( \lambda_2\sin(2\pi(n\Phi+\theta)) \psi_{n}^+ + (\lambda_2 \cos(2\pi(n\Phi+\theta)) - i\lambda_2')\psi_{n}^-\right),\\
        [W\psi]_n^- & = \lambda_1 \left( \lambda_2\sin(2\pi((n+1)\Phi+\theta)) \psi_{n+1}^+ + (\lambda_2 \cos(2\pi((n+1)\Phi+\theta)) - i\lambda_2')\psi_{n+1}^-\right) \\
        & \qquad + \lambda_1' \left((\lambda_2 \cos(2\pi(n\Phi+\theta)) + i\lambda_2')\psi_{n}^+  -\lambda_2 \sin(2\pi(n\Phi+\theta))\psi_{n}^-\right).

Let us now explain how quasiperiodic cocycles arise in the spectral analysis of the operators $W_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,\Phi,\theta}$. To study the spectral problem associated with a walk $W = S_\lambda Q$, one naturally studies the generalized eigenvalue equation $W\psi = z \psi$ with $z \in {\mathbb{C}}$, which leads to the transfer matrices defined by $$\label{eq:model:transmatDef}
    T_{z}(n)=\frac1{q^{22}_n}\begin{bmatrix}\lambda^{-1}z^{-1}\det Q_n+\lambda'\lambda^{-1}(q_n^{21}-q_n^{12})+z{\lambda'}^2\lambda^{-1}    &   q_n^{12}-\lambda'z  \\  -q_n^{21}-\lambda'z &   \lambda z   \end{bmatrix}.$$ We will show that $$\begin{bmatrix}\psi_{n+1}^+\\\psi_{n}^-\end{bmatrix}
    = T_{z}(n)\begin{bmatrix}\psi_{n}^+\\\psi_{n-1}^-\end{bmatrix}$$ whenever $z \in {\mathbb{C}}\setminus \{0\}$ and $\psi$ solves $W\psi = z \psi$ (see Section <a href="#sec:tms" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="sec:tms">[sec:tms]</a> for details).

In the primary quasiperiodic setting of this paper with coins $Q_n=Q_{\lambda_2,\Phi,\theta,n}$ given in <a href="#eq:moddefs:coinDef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:moddefs:coinDef">[eq:moddefs:coinDef]</a>, this leads naturally to a quasiperiodic cocycle. To describe this more precisely, given $\lambda_1$, $\lambda_2$, $\Phi$, $\theta$, and $z$, define $A_z(\theta)
 = A_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,z}(\theta)$ to be $T_z(0)$ as in <a href="#eq:model:transmatDef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:model:transmatDef">[eq:model:transmatDef]</a> with $Q_n$ as in <a href="#eq:moddefs:coinDef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:moddefs:coinDef">[eq:moddefs:coinDef]</a>, that is, $$\label{eq:AlambdaCocycleDef}
A_z(\theta)
= \frac{1}{\lambda_2 {\mathrm{c}}(\theta) - i\lambda_2'}
\begin{bmatrix}\lambda_1^{-1}z^{-1}+2\lambda_1'\lambda_1^{-1}\lambda_2 {\mathrm{s}}(\theta) + z{\lambda_1'}^2\lambda_1^{-1}    &   -\lambda_2 {\mathrm{s}}(\theta)-\lambda_1'z    \\  - \lambda_2 {\mathrm{s}}(\theta) -\lambda_1'z  &   \lambda_1z  \end{bmatrix},$$ where we adopt the abbreviations $$\begin{aligned}
 \label{eq:costwopiDef}
{\mathrm{c}}(\theta) = \cos(2\pi\theta), \qquad
{\mathrm{s}}(\theta) = \sin(2\pi \theta).
\end{aligned}$$ This defines a cocycle map, whose iterates and Lyapunov exponent may be considered as in <a href="#eq:cociterates" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:cociterates">[eq:cociterates]</a> and <a href="#eq:leDefinition" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:leDefinition">[eq:leDefinition]</a>.

As already mentioned, one can simply start from the model defined in <a href="#eq:moddefs:walkDef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:moddefs:walkDef">[eq:moddefs:walkDef]</a>, <a href="#eq:moddefs:slambdaDef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:moddefs:slambdaDef">[eq:moddefs:slambdaDef]</a>, and <a href="#eq:moddefs:coinDef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:moddefs:coinDef">[eq:moddefs:coinDef]</a>, but it is helpful to see how this arises physically, which also explains the choice of the model.

Let us recall the two-dimensional magnetic QW model of . The state space will be ${\mathscr{H}}_2 : = \ell^2({\mathbb{Z}}^2) \otimes {\mathbb{C}}^2$ with orthonormal basis $$\{\delta_{\underline n}^s := \delta_{\underline n} \otimes e_s: \underline n \in {\mathbb{Z}}^2, \ s \in \{\pm\} = {\mathbb{Z}}_2 \}.$$ As before, view ${\mathbb{C}}^2 = \ell^2({\mathbb{Z}}_2)$ and write $e_+ = [1,0]^\top$ and $e_- = [0,1]^\top$. Fix a magnetic flux $\Phi$. In the symmetric gauge, the magnetic translations are given by $$\begin{aligned}
 T_1 & = T_{1,\Phi} : \delta_{\underline n}^s \mapsto e^{-si  \pi \Phi n_2}\delta_{\underline n + s e_1}^s, \\
 T_2 & = T_{2,\Phi} : \delta_{\underline n}^s \mapsto e^{si  \pi \Phi n_1}\delta_{\underline n + s e_2}^s

\end{aligned}$$ Viewing ${\mathscr{H}}_2 = \ell^2({\mathbb{Z}}^2) \oplus \ell^2({\mathbb{Z}}^2)$ in the natural manner, we have $$T_{j,\Phi} = \begin{bmatrix}
 U_{j,\Phi} & 0 \\ 0 & U_{j,\Phi}^*
\end{bmatrix}$$ where $U_j=U_{j,\Phi}$ are the corresponding shifts on $\ell^2({\mathbb{Z}})$. Again in the symmetric gauge, one can take $$\begin{aligned}
U_{1,\Phi}:\delta_{{\underline{n}}} \mapsto e^{-i\pi \Phi n_{2}} \delta_{{\underline{n}}+ e_1}, \quad
U_{2,\Phi}:\delta_{{\underline{n}}} \mapsto e^{ i\pi \Phi n_{1}} \delta_{{\underline{n}}+ e_2}.
\end{aligned}$$ We now also introduce the coupling parameter $\lambda \in [0,1]$ to get the coupled operators $T_{j,\lambda,\Phi}$ given by $$\begin{aligned}
T_{j,\lambda,\Phi} = \begin{bmatrix} U_{j,\Phi} & 0 \\ 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix} 
\begin{bmatrix} \lambda & -\lambda' \\ \lambda' & \lambda \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix}1 & 0 \\ 0 & U_{j,\Phi}^* \end{bmatrix}
= \begin{bmatrix}
\lambda U_j & -\lambda' \\ \lambda' & \lambda U_j^*
\end{bmatrix}
\end{aligned}$$

\end{aligned}$$ Viewing ${\mathscr{H}}_2 = \ell^2({\mathbb{Z}}^2) \oplus \ell^2({\mathbb{Z}}^2)$ in the natural manner, we have $$T_{j,\Phi} = \begin{bmatrix}
 U_{j,\Phi} & 0 \\ 0 & U_{j,\Phi}^*
\end{bmatrix}$$ where $U_j=U_{j,\Phi}$ are the corresponding shifts on $\ell^2({\mathbb{Z}})$. Again in the symmetric gauge, one can take $$\begin{aligned}
U_{1,\Phi}:\delta_{{\underline{n}}} \mapsto e^{-i\pi \Phi n_{2}} \delta_{{\underline{n}}+ e_1}, \quad
U_{2,\Phi}:\delta_{{\underline{n}}} \mapsto e^{ i\pi \Phi n_{1}} \delta_{{\underline{n}}+ e_2}.
\end{aligned}$$ We now also introduce the coupling parameter $\lambda \in [0,1]$ to get the coupled operators $T_{j,\lambda,\Phi}$ given by $$\begin{aligned}
T_{j,\lambda,\Phi} = \begin{bmatrix} U_{j,\Phi} & 0 \\ 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix} 
\begin{bmatrix} \lambda & -\lambda' \\ \lambda' & \lambda \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix}1 & 0 \\ 0 & U_{j,\Phi}^* \end{bmatrix}
= \begin{bmatrix}
\lambda U_j & -\lambda' \\ \lambda' & \lambda U_j^*
\end{bmatrix}
\end{aligned}$$

Let us briefly explain the terminology. We call $\lambda$ a “coupling constant” to elucidate an analogy with the self-adjoint setting. Namely, $\lambda$ is a parameter that dictates how strongly neighboring sites interact with one another by mediating the strength of the shift relative to the coins. Thus, as $\lambda$ decreases from one to zero, neighboring sites interact less and less and hence are less coupled together. Moreover, the main model of the present paper experiences a phase transition in the coupling constants that is similar to the phase transition exhibited in the self-adjoint Harper’s model and that is unitary for each choice of parameters, which in turn requires genuine care in the definition of the model.

Denoting by $$C_0 = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \begin{bmatrix}
1 & i \\ -i & -1
\end{bmatrix},$$ we then want to consider $$W^{(2)} = W^{(2)}_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,\Phi} = T_{1,\lambda_1,\Phi} C_0 T_{2,\lambda_2,\Phi} C_0,$$ see Figure <a href="#fig:neigh" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="fig:neigh">[fig:neigh]</a>. The coin $C_0$ is chosen to be a conjugate of the Hadamard coin, which is a popular choice for an unbiased coin in the quantum walk setting. The particular conjugate is chosen so that our quantum walk has a relatively simple form, yet other choices are possible (see the recent experimental work ).

**Proposition 17**. *Suppose $\lambda \in (0,1]$ and $W = S_\lambda Q$ is a split-step walk with coupling constant $\lambda$ and coins $\{Q_n\}_{n\in{\mathbb{Z}}}$ as in <a href="#eq:moddefs:walkDef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:moddefs:walkDef">[eq:moddefs:walkDef]</a>.*

1.  *If $z \in {\mathbb{C}}\setminus \{0\}$, $W\psi = z\psi$, and $Q_n$ is not an off-diagonal matrix, then $$\label{eq:tm:main1}
        \begin{bmatrix}\psi_{n+1}^+\\\psi_{n}^-\end{bmatrix}
        = T_z(n)\begin{bmatrix}\psi_{n}^+\\\psi_{n-1}^-\end{bmatrix},$$ where $T_z(n)$ is given by <a href="#eq:model:transmatDef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:model:transmatDef">[eq:model:transmatDef]</a>.*

2.  *If $z \in {\mathbb{C}}\setminus \{0\}$, $W^\top \psi = z\psi$, and $Q_n$ is not an off-diagonal matrix, then $$\label{eq:tm:main1dual}
        \begin{bmatrix}\psi_{n+1}^+\\\psi_{n}^-\end{bmatrix}
        = \overline{T_{1/\bar{z}}(n)}
        \begin{bmatrix}\psi_{n}^+\\\psi_{n-1}^-\end{bmatrix}.$$*

3.  *If $z \in {\mathbb{C}}\setminus\{0\}$ and $Q_n$ is not off-diagonal, $$\label{eq:tm:main2}
    \det T_z(n) = \frac{q_n^{11}}{q_n^{22}},$$ which is unimodular.*

