Recall that the cocycle map $A_z = A_{\lambda_1, \lambda_2,z}$ is given by <a href="#eq:AlambdaCocycleDef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:AlambdaCocycleDef">[eq:AlambdaCocycleDef]</a> and the regularized cocyle $B_z = B_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,z}$ is given by <a href="#eq:cocycle:BzRegularizedDef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:cocycle:BzRegularizedDef">[eq:cocycle:BzRegularizedDef]</a>. As before, to keep the notation cleaner in this section, we view $\lambda_1$ and $\lambda_2$ as fixed and suppress them from the notation, writing $A_z(\theta)$ and $B_z(\theta)$ for $A_{\lambda_1, \lambda_2,z}(\theta)$ and $B_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,z}(\theta)$.

Let us point out the following: $B_z$ is always analytic, but (as we will see shortly), $A_z$ has singularities at some complex phases. We will see concrete manifestations of this in the graph of $L(\Phi, A_z, \varepsilon)$, which we will see is *not* convex. However, it is convex on subintervals of the $\varepsilon$-axis that avoid values of $\varepsilon$ for which $A_z(\cdot  + i\varepsilon)$ has singularities. We will see that there are two such values when $0<\lambda_2<1$ and only one when $\lambda_2=1$, and moreover the exceptional values of $\varepsilon$ are explicit functions of the coupling constant attached to the coin sequence. Indeed, let us define $\varepsilon_0$ by $$\label{eq:cocycle:eps0Def}
\sinh(2\pi\varepsilon_0) = \lambda_2'/\lambda_2,$$ (formally allowing $\varepsilon_0=\infty$ when $\lambda_2=0$). Recalling Lemma <a href="#lem:le:logIntegral" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:le:logIntegral">21</a>, the Lyapunov exponents of the complexifications of the cocycles $A_z$ and $B_z$ are related via $$\label{eq:cocycle:LAtoLB}
L(\Phi,B_z,\varepsilon)
= L(\Phi,A_z,\varepsilon) + 2\pi \max\{|\varepsilon|-\varepsilon_0,0\}.$$ In particular, $L(\Phi,A_z,\varepsilon) = L(\Phi,B_z,\varepsilon)$ whenever $|\varepsilon| \leq \varepsilon_0$.

Let us point out the following: $B_z$ is always analytic, but (as we will see shortly), $A_z$ has singularities at some complex phases. We will see concrete manifestations of this in the graph of $L(\Phi, A_z, \varepsilon)$, which we will see is *not* convex. However, it is convex on subintervals of the $\varepsilon$-axis that avoid values of $\varepsilon$ for which $A_z(\cdot  + i\varepsilon)$ has singularities. We will see that there are two such values when $0<\lambda_2<1$ and only one when $\lambda_2=1$, and moreover the exceptional values of $\varepsilon$ are explicit functions of the coupling constant attached to the coin sequence. Indeed, let us define $\varepsilon_0$ by $$\label{eq:cocycle:eps0Def}
\sinh(2\pi\varepsilon_0) = \lambda_2'/\lambda_2,$$ (formally allowing $\varepsilon_0=\infty$ when $\lambda_2=0$). Recalling Lemma <a href="#lem:le:logIntegral" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:le:logIntegral">21</a>, the Lyapunov exponents of the complexifications of the cocycles $A_z$ and $B_z$ are related via $$\label{eq:cocycle:LAtoLB}
L(\Phi,B_z,\varepsilon)
= L(\Phi,A_z,\varepsilon) + 2\pi \max\{|\varepsilon|-\varepsilon_0,0\}.$$ In particular, $L(\Phi,A_z,\varepsilon) = L(\Phi,B_z,\varepsilon)$ whenever $|\varepsilon| \leq \varepsilon_0$.

We begin with our first key technical result: by Proposition <a href="#prop:cocycle:tmMain" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="prop:cocycle:tmMain">17</a> $$\label{eq:AlambdaDet}
\det A_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,z}(\theta) = \frac{\lambda_2 \cos(2\pi \theta) + i\lambda_2'}{\lambda_2 \cos(2\pi \theta) - i \lambda_2'},$$ so $A_z$ is not always a unimodular cocycle. Nevertheless, the acceleration of $A_z$ and the acceleration of all cocycles arising from $A_z$ via complexification of the phase are always integer-valued.

<div class="lemma">

**Lemma 26**. *Fix $0<\lambda_1 \leq 1$, $0 \leq \lambda_2 \leq 1$, $\Phi \in {\mathbb{T}}\setminus {\mathbb{Q}}$, and $z \in \partial {\mathbb{D}}$, and let $A = A_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,z}$ and $B_z = B_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,z}$. We have $$\label{eq:cocycle:accelAB}
 \omega(A,\varepsilon) \in {\mathbb{Z}}\ \forall \varepsilon \neq \pm \varepsilon_0 , \quad \text{ and } \quad \omega(B,\varepsilon) \in {\mathbb{Z}}\ \forall \varepsilon \in {\mathbb{R}},$$ where $\varepsilon_0$ is as in <a href="#eq:cocycle:eps0Def" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:cocycle:eps0Def">[eq:cocycle:eps0Def]</a>.*

</div>

<div class="proof">

*Proof.* **Case 1: $\lambda_2=0$.** In this case, $A$ and $B$ are constant cocycles, so the result follows.

Recall that $\varepsilon_0$ is given by <a href="#eq:cocycle:eps0Def" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:cocycle:eps0Def">[eq:cocycle:eps0Def]</a>. Note that the denominator of <a href="#eq:cocycle:cxADet" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:cocycle:cxADet">[eq:cocycle:cxADet]</a> vanishes if and only if $\theta = 1/4 \ \mathrm{mod} \ {\mathbb{Z}}$ and $\varepsilon = -\varepsilon_0$ or $\theta = 3/4 \ \mathrm{mod} \ {\mathbb{Z}}$ and $\varepsilon = \varepsilon_0$. In particular, the cocycle $A(\cdot + i\varepsilon)$ has singularities when $|\varepsilon|=\varepsilon_0$ and is analytic otherwise. Similarly, the numerator of <a href="#eq:cocycle:cxADet" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:cocycle:cxADet">[eq:cocycle:cxADet]</a> has a root if and only if $\varepsilon = \pm \varepsilon_0$.

Since $\lambda_2< 1$, a direct calculation (using Proposition <a href="#prop:cocycle:tmMain" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="prop:cocycle:tmMain">17</a>) yields $$\label{eq:cocycle:detPM} 
\det(A(\theta)) \in {\left\{ e^{is} :0< 2\arctan(\lambda_2'/\lambda_2)\leq s \leq 2(\pi - 2\arctan(\lambda_2'/\lambda_2)) < 2\pi \right\}}.$$ In particular, the image of $\theta \mapsto  \det(A(\theta))$ lies in a simply connected subset of ${\mathbb{C}}\setminus\{0\}$ and hence $\theta \mapsto \det(A(\theta))$ has trivial winding around the origin. Since $\det(A(\xi)) \neq 0$ for all $\xi$ with $|{\mathrm{Im}}(\xi)| <  \varepsilon_0$, $$\label{eq:cocycle:winding}
\theta \mapsto \det A(\theta+i\varepsilon) \text{ has trivial winding aroung the origin}$$ for all $|\varepsilon|<\varepsilon_0$. Similarly, one can check that if $|\varepsilon|$ is sufficiently large, $$\left|1 - \det(A(\theta+i\varepsilon)) \right| < \frac{1}{2} \quad  \text{ for all } \theta \in {\mathbb{T}}.$$ Consequently, $\theta\mapsto \det(A(\theta+i\varepsilon))$ has trivial winding around zero for such large $|\varepsilon|$, and hence <a href="#eq:cocycle:winding" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:cocycle:winding">[eq:cocycle:winding]</a> also holds true for all $|\varepsilon|>\varepsilon_0$. Thus, for all $\varepsilon \neq \pm\varepsilon_0$, $\det(A(\theta+i\varepsilon,z))$ enjoys a holomorphic square root, so <a href="#eq:cocycle:accelAB" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:cocycle:accelAB">[eq:cocycle:accelAB]</a> for $A$ and $\varepsilon\neq\pm \varepsilon_0$ follows by applying Theorem <a href="#t:avilaGlobal" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="t:avilaGlobal">24</a> to $A(\cdot,z)/\sqrt{\det A(\cdot,z)}$. As discussed above, the claim for $B$ follows by applying <a href="#eq:cocycle:LAtoLB" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:cocycle:LAtoLB">[eq:cocycle:LAtoLB]</a>; the extension to $\varepsilon = \pm \varepsilon_0$ follows from continuity and piecewise affinity of $\varepsilon\mapsto L(\Phi, B,\varepsilon)$.

*Proof.* Note that the inverse of $A_{z}(\theta)$ is given by $$A_z(\theta)^{-1}
= \frac{1}{\lambda_2 {\mathrm{c}}(\theta) + i\lambda_2'}
\begin{bmatrix}     \lambda_1z  &   \lambda_2 {\mathrm{s}}(\theta) +\lambda_1'z    \\   \lambda_2 {\mathrm{s}}(\theta) + \lambda_1'z  
& \lambda_1^{-1}z^{-1}+2\lambda_1'\lambda_1^{-1}\lambda_2 {\mathrm{s}}(\theta) + z{\lambda_1'}^2\lambda_1^{-1} \end{bmatrix}$$ One has $$\begin{aligned}
    \nonumber
    R^{-1}A_z(\theta)^{-1}R
    & =  \begin{bmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ -1 & 0 \end{bmatrix} A_z(\theta)^{-1} \begin{bmatrix} 0 & -1 \\ 1 & 0 \end{bmatrix}\\
    \nonumber
    & = \frac{1}{\lambda_2 {\mathrm{c}}(\theta) + i\lambda_2'}
    \begin{bmatrix}     \lambda_1^{-1}z^{-1}+2\lambda_1'\lambda_1^{-1}\lambda_2 {\mathrm{s}}(\theta) + z{\lambda_1'}^2\lambda_1^{-1}   
    &   -(\lambda_2 {\mathrm{s}}(\theta) +\lambda_1'z) \\   
    -(\lambda_2 {\mathrm{s}}(\theta) + \lambda_1'z)    
    & \lambda_1z    \end{bmatrix}

\end{aligned}$$ so, exploiting ${\mathrm{s}}(1/2-\theta)= {\mathrm{s}}(\theta)$ and ${\mathrm{c}}(1/2-\theta) = -{\mathrm{c}}(\theta)$ give us $$\begin{aligned}
    & \ R^{-1}A_z(\theta)^{-1}R \\
     = &\ \frac{-1}{\lambda_2 {\mathrm{c}}(1/2-\theta) - i\lambda_2'}
    \begin{bmatrix}     \lambda_1^{-1}z^{-1}+2\lambda_1'\lambda_1^{-1}\lambda_2 {\mathrm{s}}(1/2-\theta) + z{\lambda_1'}^2\lambda_1^{-1}   
    &   -(\lambda_2 {\mathrm{s}}(1/2-\theta) +\lambda_1'z) \\   
    -(\lambda_2 {\mathrm{s}}(1/2-\theta) + \lambda_1'z)    
    & \lambda_1z    \end{bmatrix}   \\
    = & \ -A_z\left(\frac{1}{2}-\theta\right),

\end{aligned}$$ proving <a href="#eq:pi/2inverse" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:pi/2inverse">[eq:pi/2inverse]</a>. The identity <a href="#eq:pi/2inverseDual" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:pi/2inverseDual">[eq:pi/2inverseDual]</a> follows immediately from <a href="#eq:pi/2inverse" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:pi/2inverse">[eq:pi/2inverse]</a> and <a href="#eq:models:Asharpdef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:models:Asharpdef">[eq:models:Asharpdef]</a>. ◻

