Crucial in the proof of Theorem <a href="#t:contspec:selfdual" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="t:contspec:selfdual">32</a> is a dynamical reformulation of duality, which we presently make precise. If $\psi$ is an $\ell^2$-eigenfunction of $W_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,\Phi,\theta}$, then Theorem <a href="#t:aubryViaSolutions" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="t:aubryViaSolutions">4</a> implies that $\exp(2\pi i \theta n) \check{\phi}(n\Phi+\xi)$ is a solution of $W^{\sharp}_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,\Phi,\xi} \phi=z\phi$ for a.e. $\xi$ (with $\check{\phi}$ defined by <a href="#eq:phidef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:phidef">[eq:phidef]</a>). Consequently, we have $$\begin{aligned}
\begin{bmatrix}e^{2\pi i\theta}\check\phi^+(x+\Phi)\\\check\phi^-(x)\end{bmatrix}
\label{eq:contspec:dualTM1}
    = & \ A_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,z}^{\sharp}(x)\begin{bmatrix}\check\phi^+(x)\\e^{-2\pi i\theta}\check\phi^-(x-\Phi)\end{bmatrix}
\end{aligned}$$ for a.e. $x$, with $A^{\sharp}$ defined in <a href="#eq:models:Asharpdef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:models:Asharpdef">[eq:models:Asharpdef]</a>. Now, substitute $\hat{x} = 1/2-x$ for $x$ and apply <a href="#eq:pi/2inverse" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:pi/2inverse">[eq:pi/2inverse]</a> to get $$\begin{bmatrix}
e^{2\pi i\theta}\check\phi^+(1/2-x+\Phi)\\
\check\phi^-(1/2-x)\end{bmatrix}
= -R^{-1}A_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,z}^{\sharp}(x)^{-1} R\begin{bmatrix}
    \check\phi^+(1/2-x)\\
    e^{-2\pi i\theta}\check\phi^-(1/2-x-\Phi)\end{bmatrix}.$$ Use <a href="#eq:AlambdaDet" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:AlambdaDet">[eq:AlambdaDet]</a> and the definition of $R$ to see $$\label{eq:contspec:dualTM2b}
-A_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,z}^{\sharp}(x)
\begin{bmatrix}
-\check\phi^-(1/2-x) \\
 e^{2\pi i\theta}\check\phi^+(1/2-(x-\Phi))
\end{bmatrix}
=  e^{-2\pi i\theta}\begin{bmatrix}
    -\check\phi^-(1/2-(x+\Phi))\\
    e^{2\pi i\theta}\check\phi^+(1/2-x)\end{bmatrix}$$ Putting together <a href="#eq:contspec:dualTM1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:contspec:dualTM1">[eq:contspec:dualTM1]</a> and <a href="#eq:contspec:dualTM2b" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:contspec:dualTM2b">[eq:contspec:dualTM2b]</a>, we get $$\label{eq:reducibility}
A_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,z}^{\sharp}(x) M(x) = M(x+\Phi) \begin{bmatrix}e^{2\pi i \theta} \\ & -e^{-2\pi i \theta} \end{bmatrix},$$ where $$\label{eq:Mreducible}
M(x)= \begin{bmatrix}\check\phi^+(x) & -\check\phi^-(1/2-x)\\
e^{-2\pi i\theta}\check\phi^-(x-\Phi)
& e^{2\pi i\theta}\check\phi^+(1/2-(x-\Phi))\end{bmatrix}.$$

<div class="proof">

*Proof of Theorem <a href="#t:contspec:selfdual" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="t:contspec:selfdual">32</a>.* Let $\lambda_1=\lambda_2 = \lambda \in (0,1)$, $\Phi$ irrational, and $\theta$ irrational with respect to $\Phi$ be given, and assume on the contrary that $W_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,\Phi,\theta}$ has nonempty point spectrum. Let $\psi$ denote a normalized eigenfunction with corresponding eigenvalue $z$. Define $\check\phi$ by <a href="#eq:phidef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:phidef">[eq:phidef]</a> and consider $M$ as in <a href="#eq:Mreducible" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:Mreducible">[eq:Mreducible]</a>. Since $|\det(A_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,z}^{\sharp}(x))|=1$, <a href="#eq:reducibility" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:reducibility">[eq:reducibility]</a> implies that $|\det(M(x))|=|\det(M(x+\Phi))|$. By ergodicity of $x\mapsto x+\Phi$ on ${\mathbb{T}}$, $|\det(M(x))|$ is a.e. constant with respect to $x$.

Also $\|M(x)\|>0$ for a.e. $x$, since if not, $\|M(x)\|=0$ for a.e. $x$ by <a href="#eq:reducibility" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:reducibility">[eq:reducibility]</a> and ergodicity of $x\mapsto x+\Phi$. However, this would imply $\check\phi_\pm(x)$ vanishes for a.e. $x$, which contradicts nontriviality of the eigenfunction $\psi$ that generates $\check{\phi}$.

Let us now consider for $n\geq 1$ the $n$-step transfer matrix given by $$A^{{\sharp}n}(x)=A_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,z}^{\sharp}(x+(n-1)\Phi)A_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,z}^{\sharp}(x+(n-2)\Phi)\ldots A_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,z}^{\sharp}(x+\Phi) A_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,z}^{\sharp}(x),$$ where we choose notation consistent with <a href="#eq:cociterates" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:cociterates">[eq:cociterates]</a>. Then, by <a href="#eq:reducibility" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:reducibility">[eq:reducibility]</a> $$\label{eq:AAubryDualn}
A^{{\sharp}n}(x)=M(x+n\Phi)
        \begin{bmatrix}
            e^{2\pi i\theta} &0\\
            0& -e^{-2\pi i\theta} 
        \end{bmatrix}^n  M(x)^{-1}.$$

We define $$\begin{aligned}
\Psi^{(n)}(x)
& = \mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}A^{{\sharp}n}(x) - \mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\left( 
\begin{bmatrix}
e^{2\pi i\theta} &0\\
0& -e^{-2\pi i\theta} 
\end{bmatrix}^n \right)\label{eq:Psi^n} \\
\label{eq:Psi^nb}
& = \mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}A^{{\sharp}n}(x) -(e^{2\pi i n \theta} + (-1)^n e^{-2\pi i n \theta}),
\end{aligned}$$ and note that $$\begin{aligned}
\Psi^{(n)}(x) 
= \mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\left(\Big( M(x+n\Phi)-M(x) \Big)
\begin{bmatrix}
e^{2\pi i\theta} &0\\
0& -e^{-2\pi i\theta} 
\end{bmatrix}^n  M(x)^{-1}\right).
\end{aligned}$$ Since we have the inequality $|\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}(\mathfrak A)| \leq 2\|\mathfrak A\|$ and the identity $\|\mathfrak A^{-1}\| = \|\mathfrak A\|/|\det(\mathfrak A)|$, we have $$|\Psi^{(n)}(x)|\leq \frac{2}{|\det M|}\Vert M(x+n\Phi)-M(x)\Vert \Vert M(x)\Vert.$$ By the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality, $$\Vert\Psi^{(n)}(x)\Vert_{L^1}\leq \frac{2}{|\det M|}\Vert M(x+n\Phi)-M(x)\Vert_{L^2} \Vert M(x)\Vert_{L^2}.$$ Note that $\Vert M(x)\Vert _{L^2}$ is finite by unitarity of the inverse Fourier transform. This also implies that $\Vert\Psi^{(n)}\Vert_{L^1}$ can be made arbitrarily small by making $\mathrm{dist}(n\Phi,{\mathbb{Z}})$ sufficiently small. We then have $$\label{eq:L1=0}
\liminf_{n\to\infty}\Vert\Psi^{(n)}(x)\Vert_{L^1}=0$$ On the other hand, by <a href="#eq:AlambdaCocycleDef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:AlambdaCocycleDef">[eq:AlambdaCocycleDef]</a>, <a href="#eq:models:Asharpdef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:models:Asharpdef">[eq:models:Asharpdef]</a>, and <a href="#eq:Psi^n" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:Psi^n">[eq:Psi^n]</a> we notice that $\Psi^{(n)}$ is a trigonometric polynomial divided by $$\label{eq:Qn}
\mathcal Q^{(n)}_1
= \mathcal Q^{(n)}_1(x)
:=\prod_{k=0}^{n-1}q_{11}(x+k\Phi)
=\prod_{k=0}^{n-1} (\lambda\cos(2\pi(x+k\Phi) + i\lambda')  .$$ By we can control this quantity with the help of Lemma <a href="#lem:le:logIntegral" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:le:logIntegral">21</a> with $\varepsilon = 0$. Thus we can modify <a href="#eq:L1=0" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:L1=0">[eq:L1=0]</a> to be $$\label{eq:L1=0.Q}
\liminf_{n\to\infty}\left\Vert  \left(\frac{1+\lambda'}{2}\right)^{-n}\mathcal Q^{(n)}_1(x) \Psi^{(n)}(x)\right \Vert_{L^1}=0$$

We define $$\begin{aligned}
\Psi^{(n)}(x)
& = \mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}A^{{\sharp}n}(x) - \mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\left( 
\begin{bmatrix}
e^{2\pi i\theta} &0\\
0& -e^{-2\pi i\theta} 
\end{bmatrix}^n \right)\label{eq:Psi^n} \\
\label{eq:Psi^nb}
& = \mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}A^{{\sharp}n}(x) -(e^{2\pi i n \theta} + (-1)^n e^{-2\pi i n \theta}),
\end{aligned}$$ and note that $$\begin{aligned}
\Psi^{(n)}(x) 
= \mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\left(\Big( M(x+n\Phi)-M(x) \Big)
\begin{bmatrix}
e^{2\pi i\theta} &0\\
0& -e^{-2\pi i\theta} 
\end{bmatrix}^n  M(x)^{-1}\right).
\end{aligned}$$ Since we have the inequality $|\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}(\mathfrak A)| \leq 2\|\mathfrak A\|$ and the identity $\|\mathfrak A^{-1}\| = \|\mathfrak A\|/|\det(\mathfrak A)|$, we have $$|\Psi^{(n)}(x)|\leq \frac{2}{|\det M|}\Vert M(x+n\Phi)-M(x)\Vert \Vert M(x)\Vert.$$ By the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality, $$\Vert\Psi^{(n)}(x)\Vert_{L^1}\leq \frac{2}{|\det M|}\Vert M(x+n\Phi)-M(x)\Vert_{L^2} \Vert M(x)\Vert_{L^2}.$$ Note that $\Vert M(x)\Vert _{L^2}$ is finite by unitarity of the inverse Fourier transform. This also implies that $\Vert\Psi^{(n)}\Vert_{L^1}$ can be made arbitrarily small by making $\mathrm{dist}(n\Phi,{\mathbb{Z}})$ sufficiently small. We then have $$\label{eq:L1=0}
\liminf_{n\to\infty}\Vert\Psi^{(n)}(x)\Vert_{L^1}=0$$ On the other hand, by <a href="#eq:AlambdaCocycleDef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:AlambdaCocycleDef">[eq:AlambdaCocycleDef]</a>, <a href="#eq:models:Asharpdef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:models:Asharpdef">[eq:models:Asharpdef]</a>, and <a href="#eq:Psi^n" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:Psi^n">[eq:Psi^n]</a> we notice that $\Psi^{(n)}$ is a trigonometric polynomial divided by $$\label{eq:Qn}
\mathcal Q^{(n)}_1
= \mathcal Q^{(n)}_1(x)
:=\prod_{k=0}^{n-1}q_{11}(x+k\Phi)
=\prod_{k=0}^{n-1} (\lambda\cos(2\pi(x+k\Phi) + i\lambda')  .$$ By we can control this quantity with the help of Lemma <a href="#lem:le:logIntegral" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:le:logIntegral">21</a> with $\varepsilon = 0$. Thus we can modify <a href="#eq:L1=0" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:L1=0">[eq:L1=0]</a> to be $$\label{eq:L1=0.Q}
\liminf_{n\to\infty}\left\Vert  \left(\frac{1+\lambda'}{2}\right)^{-n}\mathcal Q^{(n)}_1(x) \Psi^{(n)}(x)\right \Vert_{L^1}=0$$

We observe from <a href="#eq:Psi^nb" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:Psi^nb">[eq:Psi^nb]</a> that $$\label{eq:QPsi}
\mathcal Q^{(n)}_1 \Psi^{(n)}= \mathcal Q^{(n)}_1(x) \mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}A^{{\sharp}n}(x)-\mathcal Q^{(n)}_1(x) (e^{2\pi i n \theta} + (-1)^n e^{-2\pi i n \theta}).$$ It is clear that the second term on the right hand side of the above equation is a constant multiple of the trigonometric polynomial, $\mathcal{Q}_1^{(n)}(x)$, (recall that $\theta$ is currently fixed). By <a href="#eq:AlambdaCocycleDef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:AlambdaCocycleDef">[eq:AlambdaCocycleDef]</a> and <a href="#eq:models:Asharpdef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:models:Asharpdef">[eq:models:Asharpdef]</a>, it is also true that $\mathcal Q^{(n)}_1 \mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}A^{{\sharp}n}(x)$ is a trigonometric polynomial. We will estimate the leading coefficients of these trigonometric polynomials, that is, the coefficients of the $e^{2\pi i nx}$ and $e^{-2\pi i nx}$ terms. One sees immediately that the leading coefficients of $\mathcal{Q}_1^{(n)}$ have absolute value $(\lambda/2)^n$.
